\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Genome Selection in Plants
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Luis Garreta
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Motivation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Marker assisted selection (MAS) exploits the markers associated with trait
 of interest for selecting lines with superior allele for developing improved
 superior lines.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
However use of MAS is restricted to simple traits due to its inability to
 handle complex traits as well as higher genotyping cost.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Advancement in genomic technologies has been able to reduce the cost of
 genotyping drastically enabling the use of genome-wide marker data for
 selecting lines with higher breeding value.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Genomic selection (GS), a modern breeding approach that uses using genome-wide
 maker data to estimate the breeding value, has the potential to address
 the complex traits.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
GS exploits the genotyping and phenotyping data on training population and
 establishes the prediction models to calculate the genomic estimated breeding
 value (GEBV) using genotyping data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
GS has the capability to reduce selection duration, increase selection accuracy,
 intensity, efficiency and gains per unit of time, and thereby enhancing
 the rate of genetic gains.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Availability of cost effective genotyping platforms has enabled the generation
 of large scale genotyping data in much less cost and faster manner, enabling
 the deployment of GS in several plant species.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
GS uses a ‘training population’ of individuals that have been both phenotyped
 and genotyped to develop a model for calculating genomic estimated breeding
 values (GEBVs).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Subsequently by using this model, GEBVs can be calculated for untested individua
ls from a ‘candidate population’ and selection candidates (SCs) for making
 the crosses can be identified.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Although GEBVs are not the function of the underlying QTLs/genes for the
 trait, they are the ideal selection criterion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
GS basically attempts to capture the total additive genetic variance with
 genome-wide marker coverage and effect estimates.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Therefore, selection of an individual without phenotypic data can be performed
 based on this model (predicting the individual’s breeding value).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The models can be used to calculate GEBVs that help breeder to identify
 offspring that will be good parents in the next generation, based solely
 on genotypic information about an existing line.
\end_layout

